problem_prompt: Approach the following question the way someone in elementary school would. What is the units digit of $\frac{20 \cdot 21 \cdot 22 \cdot 23 \cdot 24 \cdot 25}{1000}$?
gpt_response:
To find the units digit of $\frac{20 \cdot 21 \cdot 22 \cdot 23 \cdot 24 \cdot 25}{1000}$, we can simplify the numerator first.

When we multiply all the numbers together, we get $20 \times 21 \times 22 \times 23 \times 24 \times 25 = 2^{2} \times 2 \times 5 \times 3 \times 11 \times 2^{3} \times 5^{2} = 2^{6} \times 3 \times 5^{3} \times 11$.

This simplifies to $2^{6} \times 3 \times 5^{3} \times 11 = 64 \times 3 \times 125 \times 11 = 240 \times 125 \times 11 = 3000 \times 11 = 33000$.

Now we need to divide $33000$ by $1000$ to find the units digit. Since $33000$ divided by $1000$ equals $33$, the units digit is $\boxed{0}$.
